            <p>S. MORAIS<lb/>
                546 NORTH FIFTH ST.&#44;<lb/></p>
            <p>Philadelphia&#44; November 1st 1888<lb/></p>
            <p>S. N. Carvalho Esq<lb/></p>
            <p>My Dear Sir<lb/></p>
            <p>Allow me to express my<lb/> satisfaction at having heard you read the introduction<lb/> to the literary work which you intend publishing.<lb/>  From it I learned that we share the same views as<lb/> to the importance of vindicating the Hebrew Scriptures&#44;<lb/>&#45;&#45;chiefly the cosmogony of Genesis&#45;&#45;from the aspersersions<lb/> of unbelievers.  I hail with <del>with</del> pleasure<lb/> every effort in that direction by persons of a reverent<lb/> nature equipped with the requisite knowledge.<lb/></p>
            <p>The few pages from the book proper&#44; which you kindly<lb/> submitted to my consideration&#44; disclose conscientious studies<lb/> and varied capacities enabling you to treat the subject<lb/> intelligently and comprehensively.<lb/></p>
            
                <pb n="2"/>
            <p>I shall not presume to say how far you have<lb/> succeeded in reconciling religion with modern science.  To<lb/> that&#44; competent men will doubtless bring a testimony<lb/> gratifying to yourself&#44; and promoting your worthy<lb/> object.<lb/></p>
            <p>With sincere wishes for a beneficial result of your<lb/> long labors&#44; and for your continual welfare.<lb/></p>
            <p>I remain<lb/>
                Yours very respectfully<lb/>
                S. Morais<lb/></p>
            </body>
    </text>
